SIMPLE: incorruptible
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incorruptible
<hw>In`cor*rupt"i*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>incorruptibilis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>incorruptible</ets>. See
<er>In-</er> not, and <er>Corrupt</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not corruptible; incapable of corruption, decay, or
dissolution; <as>as, gold is <ex>incorruptible</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our bodies shall be changed into <qex>incorruptible</qex> and
immortal substances.</q> <rj><qau>Wake.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Incapable of being bribed or morally corrupted;
inflexibly just and upright.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incorruptible</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Incorruptible
<hw>In`cor*rupt"i*ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld>
<def>One of a religious sect which arose in Alexandria, in the reign of
the Emperor Justinian, and which believed that the body of Christ was
incorruptible, and that he suffered hunger, thirst, pain, only in
appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incorruptibleness</ent>⟦br⟧
